ce:section.ce:para:
The chemical composition of the sintered, mixed oxide preform was unchanged from the starting precursor powders as the binary phase diagram shows complete solid immiscibility below the eutectic temperature [10]. Consequently, the sintering regimen retained the distribution of elements present during the initial blending of powders and preform manufacture. At the reduction temperature of 1173K, the diffusion of tungsten in titanium is expected to be extremely slow, and a uniform distribution of WO3 is essential to obtain a uniform distribution of tungsten in the final alloy. Fig. 2
 depicts a backscattered electron image of the mixed oxide preform cross-section, and shows the finely dispersed WO3 particles. XRD analysis of the blended powder mixture and sintered preform (Fig. 3
) revealed TiO2 as the dominant phase with minor WO3 peaks as expected from the volume fraction of the constituents (95.3% TiO2, 4.7% WO3).

A backscattered electron micrograph of the reduced material (Fig. 6
) depicts a uniform distribution of tungsten throughout the alloy and the bulk composition was found to average 9.5±1wt.% W. Residual calcium chloride in the material pores was always analyzed below 1wt.% and typical values were often at the detection limit for the X-EDS technique. Lower residual levels would logically be obtained after high temperature vacuum distillation, which is used to ensure low volatile content in Kroll sponge. However, the formation of closed pores during the reduction process containing electrolyte and CaO would be problematic since the impurities would not be affected by distillation. Further analysis is needed to ascertain whether this constitutes a severe issue. No oxygen peaks were detected in the X-EDS analysis and the XRD pattern of the bulk material indicated a mixture of α- and β-Ti (Fig. 7
). There was no evidence of unreduced tungsten or titanium oxides retained in the final alloy. Compared to mechanically alloyed powder, the distribution of tungsten was superior as there were no agglomerates of fine metallic particles or large tungsten particles that had incompletely dissolved [1].

The microstructure indicates the formation of a 100% beta solid solution prior to cooling and demonstrates the capability of direct electrochemical reduction to produce homogeneous structures via a non-melt process. The level of porosity inherent in the reduced preform is dramatically less than that of the preform precursor, largely due to the enhanced solid-state sintering of metallic constituents compared to the oxide feedstocks at the reduction temperature. Fortunately, the extent of sintering did not appear to inhibit complete metallization of the preform and a microstructure typical of a slow-cooled, hypoeutectiod composition is clearly evident and is consistent with the binary phase diagram (Fig. 8
) [3]. Subject to a furnace cool (less than 3Kmin−1), the 100% β-(Ti,W) microstructure present at the reduction terminus transformed with pro-eutectoid α first forming at the β grain boundaries. The thickness of the grain boundary alpha was between 1 and 3μm. Fig. 9
 focuses on a prior β grain and depicts possible Widmanstätten α lathes at a 0.2–0.8μm length scale and a finer (∼100nm) structure arising from the eutectoid decomposition transformation occurring at 1013±20K. At present, this phenomenon is believed to be due to the slow diffusion of tungsten in titanium and is also responsible for the very fine grain sizes observed in the reduced material. From Fig. 6, the average prior β grain size is below 10–20μm, which may be to the benefit of subsequent thermomechanical processing as there is added flexibility for working within the β regime. This fine-grained, as-reduced structure is of the same size-scale as the precursor powders and may also contribute to improved mechanical properties versus conventional titanium with prior β grain sizes almost an order of magnitude larger.
